# Low-memory profile for ~16 GB machines: copy to `.env` (docker compose picks
# it up automatically) and run the stack as usual.
#
# The chat model is deliberately NOT downgraded: llama3.2:3b maps noticeably
# worse, and mapping quality is the point of the pipeline. llama3.1:8b (~5 GB
# weights + ~0.5 GB KV cache per slot) fits a 16 GB machine — the total stack
# footprint with the settings below is ~7.5 GB.
#
# On Windows/WSL hosts one extra step is required: WSL caps itself at 50% of
# host RAM (8 GB on a 16 GB machine), which is too tight. Create
# C:\Users\<you>\.wslconfig with:
#   [wsl2]
#   memory=11GB
# then `wsl --shutdown` once. Native Linux hosts need nothing.
#
# Expect CPU-only mapping to take tens of seconds per chunk (it is memory-
# bandwidth-bound); the pipeline works fine, it's just not fast. If that is
# unacceptable and quality loss is tolerable, set OLLAMA_MODEL=llama3.2:3b
# (~2 GB, ~3x faster on CPU) as the fallback tier.

# Halve the concurrent mapping calls: the KV cache scales with parallelism.
# Keep these two in sync (see docker-compose.yml).
OLLAMA_NUM_PARALLEL=2
MAP_WORKERS=2

# Release models after 5 idle minutes instead of pinning them (-1): on a tight
# machine, reclaiming ~6 GB between sessions beats always-warm starts.
OLLAMA_KEEP_ALIVE=5m
